from the western Mediterranean or Greek-speaking Christians from Constantinople but rather Christians from northern Mesopotamia who spoke the Aramaic dialect of Syriac. Living under Muslim rule from the seventh century to the present, Syriac Christians wrote the first and most extensive accounts of Islam, describing a complicated set of religious and cultural exchanges not reducible to the solely antagonistic. Through its critical introductions and new translations of this invaluable historical material, When Christians First Met Muslims allows scholars, students, and the general public to explore the earliest interactions between what eventually became the world’s two largest religions, shedding new light on Islamic history and Christian-Muslim relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslamxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aIslamvEarly works to 1800. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aancient world.  aarab politics.  aaramaic.  abeginning of islam.  abirth of islam.  achristian muslim relations.  achristianity.  achurch history.  acultural exchange.  acultural studies.  aearly islam.  ahistory.  ainterfaith.  ainterreligious studies.  aislam.  aislamic history.  aislamic studies.  amedieval studies.  amesopotamia.  amiddle east.  amohammed.  amuslim rule.  anonfiction.  apluralism.  areligion.  areligious history.  aspirituality.  asyriac christians.  asyriac.  atheology.  aworld religions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028493740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096057240uhttps://www.degruyter.co